/*
Lab 02

Objective: Use the Zeppelin platform and visualizations to find interesting things about the dataset.

"Interestingness of data"
Data is likely to be interesting if it displays large deviations (or outliers) from some reference (e.g. another dataset, historical data, or the rest of the data.)


For the taxi dataset, an uninteresting deviation would be less ridership between 2 am and 6 am. 

An interesting deviation might be the difference between travel distance and Euclidian  distance, indicating more deviation from the direct route.

Your tasks:
1) Review the columns (attributes) in the Taxi class and find interesting grouping and combinations of columns and grouping that show deviations between values.

2) Execute the code to get the data ready, up to line marked "// Queries"

3) Each set of use-cases is in one of 6 Groups. Read the introduction and execute each query.

4) There are 4 Question sections within the 6 Groups. Answer each question before moving forward.
   Cells prefilled with "your SQL code here" leave space for your answers.

*/

paragraphs.title: Counts of trip Distances
paragraphs.text:
%sql
SELECT trip_distance, count(1) value 
from taxi 
group by trip_distance 
order by trip_distance
// Outliers past trip_distance > 10 are the one offs, and are not of interest. Let's reduce the range of rows.

paragraphs.title: Counts of Trip Distances: distance < 10
paragraphs.text:
%sql
SELECT trip_distance, count(1) value 
from taxi 
WHERE trip_distance < 10 
group by trip_distance order by trip_distance
// Let's isolate the query using subquery to look at records at the top portion of the y-axis.

paragraphs.title: Counts Of Trip Distances: Distance < 10 and Count > 200
paragraphs.text:
%sql
select Q1.trip_distance, Q1.value from (
    SELECT trip_distance, count(1) value 
    from taxi 
    WHERE trip_distance < 10
    group by trip_distance order by trip_distance
) as Q1
where Q1.value > 200

paragraphs.title: histogram of Rides (Y) per passenger Count (X)
paragraphs.text:
%sql
SELECT passenger_count, count(1) value 
from taxi 
group by  passenger_count
order by passenger_count
// Let's look at groupings within the graph.

paragraphs.title: Histogram of Rides per hour
paragraphs.text:
%sql
SELECT hour(pickup_datetime) hour, count(1) value
from taxi 
group by  hour(pickup_datetime)
order by  hour(pickup_datetime)
// Let's split these graphs by the rate that was used (rate_code)

paragraphs.title: Histogram of Passengers by hour and Rate code
paragraphs.text:
%sql
SELECT hour(pickup_datetime) hour, rate_code, count(1) value
from taxi
group by  hour(pickup_datetime), rate_code
order by  hour(pickup_datetime),rate_code

// We see that most rates are at rate_code = 1.
// Let's remove this rate_code and see when other rates are used.

%sql
SELECT hour(pickup_datetime) hour, rate_code, count(1) value
from taxi 
where rate_code != 1
group by  hour(pickup_datetime), rate_code
order by  hour(pickup_datetime), rate_code
// Question 1: Is there a correlation between rate_code and distance, or time of pickup, etc?

%sql
SELECT rate_code, avg(trip_distance)
FROM taxi
GROUP BY rate_code
ORDER BY rate_code

paragraphs.title: Histogram Of Passengers Per Minute
paragraphs.text:
%sql
SELECT concat(hour(pickup_datetime),":",minute(pickup_datetime)) minute, round(avg(passenger_count),2) Passengers, count(1) value 
from taxi 
group by    concat(hour(pickup_datetime),":",minute(pickup_datetime))
order by   concat(hour(pickup_datetime),":",minute(pickup_datetime))

// Let's look at the mapping of two columns, pick hour and trip_distance. What correlation do you see? Can come to any interesting conclusions? 
// Try changing the (Y) column and see if any outliers exist at different hours of the day.

%sql

FROM taxi
WHERE trip_distance >= (sqrt( (dropoff_latitude - pickup_latitude)*(dropoff_latitude - pickup_latitude) + (dropoff_longitude - pickup_longitude)*(dropoff_longitude - pickup_longitude) ) ) AND trip_distance < 10
GROUP BY (sqrt( (dropoff_latitude - pickup_latitude)*(dropoff_latitude - pickup_latitude) + (dropoff_longitude - pickup_longitude)*(dropoff_longitude - pickup_longitude) ) )

paragraphs.text:
/*
In the next example we want to test whether there is correlation between the trip length and the number of passenger for each rate code:
- First, we divide the trips to 4 quantiles based on the trip length (0-25% qunatile, 25-50% quantile, ...).
- For each rate_code, for each qunatile, we want to find our the average number of passenger
*/

%sql
SELECT
    rate_code,
    quartile,
    AVG(passenger_count)
FROM (
  SELECT
    passenger_count,
    rate_code,
    trip_distance,
    ntile(4) OVER (PARTITION BY rate_code ORDER BY trip_distance ASC) as quartile
  FROM taxi) tmp
GROUP BY quartile, rate_code

%sql
SELECT
    rate_code,
    trip_distance,
    e_dist,
    rank
FROM (
  SELECT
    rate_code,
    trip_distance,
    round((sqrt( (dropoff_latitude - pickup_latitude)*(dropoff_latitude - pickup_latitude) + (dropoff_longitude - pickup_longitude)*(dropoff_longitude - pickup_longitude) ) ),2)
    as e_dist,
    dense_rank() OVER (PARTITION BY rate_code ORDER BY trip_distance DESC) as rank
  FROM taxi) tmp
WHERE rank <= 2
ORDER BY e_dist
